Test Cases - Unit.Unnamed: 4: User enters "On Demand Cycle Count" through the JSA Inventory handheld menu
User enters the location and priority (1-10 w/1 being highest priority) for the cycle count. Priority defaults to 5 if left empty.

The Parent LPN Screen will show the Location along with the LPN in the Location and # of items.
User will scan the LPN barcode on the pallet's label
User will be shown a list box with items on the scanned LPN that can be cycle counted
User will scan SKU and hit enter
On the next screen, user will select the pack type and enter the quantity they counted. They will also be prompted to enter the LOT number of the item they are counting.

If they enter the quantity that Deposco thinks is in the system, they'll be returned to the previous screen with the list of items to be counted. If they enter a different quantity, they will be asked to re-count and re-enter since a variance was detected.
User will be asked to re-count as many times as necessary until they either enter the same quantity twice in a row, or enter the quantity Deposco believes is in the system.
User will be returned to the item listbox screen to select another item at that location if necessary.  If not, they can select "Next Location" and repeat the process if there are more tasks
User (typically a supervisor or manager) will enter the "Manage Cycle Count Variances" UI through a laptop or desktop, located under Inventory Admin in the Application Menu
Test Cases - Unit.Unnamed: 5:
Depending on which action was taken, stock units will be updated to reflect what was counted, remain the same and cycle count task will be complete, or remain the same but generate a new cycle count task for the same location. 

The process will be repeated until either there is no variance detected, or the variance is accepted in "manage cycle count variances".

Test Cases - Unit.Unnamed: 4: A list of variances will be displayed.  A variance is any time a qty is entered that differs from what Deposco has listed in the system.
For each record you will see the item, counted qty, variance qty, reason code, and other relevant data. The columns listed can be adjusted.

Whoever is managing the variances can select the tasks and accept (stock units for that item/location will be updated based on what was counted), reject (stock unit for that location/item will remain with the same qty they had before the cycle count), or re-count (no change is made to the stock unit yet, and cycle count task is sent back to the floor to be re-counted).

UAT TEST CASES.Unnamed: 4: User enters "On Demand Cycle Count" through the JSA Inventory handheld menu
User enters the location and priority (1-10 w/1 being highest priority) for the cycle count. Priority defaults to 5 if left empty.

The Parent LPN Screen will show the Location along with the LPN in the Location and # of items.
User will scan the LPN barcode on the pallet's label
User will be shown a list box with items on the scanned LPN that can be cycle counted
User will scan SKU and hit enter
On the next screen, user will select the pack type and enter the quantity they counted. They will also be prompted to enter the LOT number of the item they are counting.

If they enter the quantity that Deposco thinks is in the system, they'll be returned to the previous screen with the list of items to be counted. If they enter a different quantity, they will be asked to re-count and re-enter since a variance was detected.
User will be asked to re-count as many times as necessary until they either enter the same quantity twice in a row, or enter the quantity Deposco believes is in the system.
User will be returned to the item listbox screen to select another item at that location if necessary.  If not, they can select "Next Location" and repeat the process if there are more tasks
User (typically a supervisor or manager) will enter the "Manage Cycle Count Variances" UI through a laptop or desktop, located under Inventory Admin in the Application Menu
UAT TEST CASES.Unnamed: 5:
Depending on which action was taken, stock units will be updated to reflect what was counted, remain the same and cycle count task will be complete, or remain the same but generate a new cycle count task for the same location.
